### 范式定位与行业标准声明
### Paradigm Positioning & Industry Standard Declaration

QNLOO-SPL（QNLOO Sovereign Public License）主权公开许可范式，是一套独立、可复用、行业通用的数字资产许可标准。本范式不属于传统免费开源协议，而是源码开放的主权商事价值分配范式。

The QNLOO-SPL (QNLOO Sovereign Public License) is an independent, reusable, and industry-universal standard for digital asset licensing. This paradigm is not a traditional free open-source license, but a sovereign commercial value distribution framework with open source code.

QNLOO-SPL范式的核心标志性特征包括：

（一）双资产分层许可隔离架构——源代码采用宽松开源协议自由开放；文本、专利、音频、体系逻辑、商用运营行为单独受主权商事许可约束；

（二）阶梯式营收分层授权体系——个人/学术永久免费；小微营收阈值内全豁免；合规主体超额营收固定比例分润；游离生态主体全额营收计费；大厂产品线穿透核算；

（三）主权法定数字货币结算机制——以发行主体所属国家法定数字货币为全球基准结算通道，配套过渡期安排，绑定本土企业完税与资金追溯合规义务；

（四）分布式社会化取证与吹哨人维权闭环——开源被动式取证工具、链上侵权指纹存证、梯度化吹哨悬赏分成、跨法系自适应权利让渡机制；

（五）梯度化公允清算违约金规则——区分无意疏漏与主观恶意逃逸两套赔付标准，违约金经完整法理论证为公允补偿而非惩罚性罚金，适配各国司法裁量标准。

The core defining features of the QNLOO-SPL paradigm include:

(a) Dual-Asset Tiered Licensing Isolation Architecture — source code is freely available under a permissive open-source license; textual, patent, audio, systemic logic, and commercial operational assets are separately governed by sovereign commercial licensing terms;

(b) Progressive Revenue-Based Tiered Authorization — permanent free use for individuals and academia; full exemption for small-scale entities within revenue thresholds; fixed-percentage revenue sharing for compliant entities with excess revenue; full-revenue billing for off-chain entities; and enterprise product-line revenue penetration;

(c) Sovereign Statutory CBDC Settlement Mechanism — the statutory digital currency of the issuing entity's home country serves as the global benchmark settlement channel, supported by transitional arrangements and binding compliance obligations for local tax and fund traceability;

(d) Distributed Socialized Evidence Collection & Qui Tam Enforcement Loop — open-source passive forensic toolkits, on-chain infringement fingerprint recording, tiered Qui Tam bounty sharing, and cross-jurisdictional adaptive right assignment mechanisms;

(e) Tiered and Fairly Estimated Liquidated Damages Rules — two sets of compensation standards distinguishing inadvertent omissions from subjective bad-faith evasion, with liquidated damages fully legally reasoned as fair compensation rather than punitive penalties, suitable for judicial discretion across sovereign courts worldwide.

